	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f103054732424379>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=>RE: now here's news to me</a> <a id=fs8 href=#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Aug 28th 11:21 AM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=61489><span id=Scholar>Kamlatir, Eater of Souls</span></a><br><b><span id=Scholar>Scholar</span></b><br><span id=notbold>66 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Let me first say that I have no idea how Fires of Heaven or whomever does their end content tanking, nor do I think it matters or sets The Standard. Common sense dictates when the pros or one class outweigh the pros of another.<br><br> It is an agreed upon fact that shadowknights in their pre disease counter patch were absolute when it came to aggro. Absolute meaning if they wanted aggro they had it, in a matter of seconds and unchallenged. However, the afore mentioned patch changed that to some degree. Paladins would beat a shadowknight in an outright aggro contest today and what's more, a properly equipped warrior would be a contender in the long run. This revolves very little around what damage is dished out, it's simply about which class's spells induce the most hate points in the least amount of time. <br><br>Proper weapons, ie Jagged Blade of War, Willsapper or better, put a warrior at a fully adequate potential aggro level although procs and thereby aggro is somewhat random. Hybrids have the advantage that they can create fast aggro and further decide exactly when, a very nice situation for high aggro casters. They could theoretically start their casting a set time from the mob is engaged and know that the mob is properly taunted. In a small enough party they could simply watch the spell messages for information on when to cast. Also, the whole pre tank concept becomes almost unnecessary with hybrids.<br><br>In my opinion the degrading of the disease cloud aggro was an unforseen effect of VI's attempt to lower the aggro that slow induced, just as I can imagine the high aggro status of shadowknights as a class wasn't an original intention by the games creators but a side effect. However, that is how it unfolded and changing that fact after three years of game play induced alot of discontent in the shadowknight society. The new spells that are undergoing testing (and are by no means certain to be taken into the game or to be introduced in their present form) seems like a way to mend the side effects of making it easier on shamans and enchanters and to restore shadowknight to their absolute status. I feel this is as it should be.<br><br>If you keep up to date with the test server happenings you will also know that the spell Harmshield (the necromancer version of Divine Aura) has been made available to shadowknights at level 51 there. Harmshield makes you invulnerable to anything but Deathtouch for 18 seconds with a recast time of 10 minutes. This is indeed a major change to the class, infusing us with what I'd term a 'raid discipline': something that can be figured into the strategies of raiding due to it's usefulness and reasonable reuse time. <br><br>To me it seems that in the quote that initiated this thread we are told about paladins tanking 'zone trash', something which the hybrids has always been superior in. The term zone trash I use for encounters that doesn't take defensive to handle which is of course somewhat dependant on your hitpoints. I can imagine that in that end phase of the game that Fires of Heaven is in their hybrids have enough hitpoints to tank what other guilds need warriors with defensive for but also that there is still encounters where warriors are a must. If the Harmshield spell goes through the testing phase I can only imagine it will step up the shadowknight tanking ability even more, not to mention the effects on pulling high damage output mobs.<br><br>All in all, it's looking up for us :)</p>&nbsp;<br></td></td></tr>
